		<title>SBL Student Spotlight &#8211; Jack Zaferes</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/notes/sbl-student-spotlight-jack-zaferes.html</link>
		<comments>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/notes/sbl-student-spotlight-jack-zaferes.html#respond</comments>
		<pubDate>Wed, 21 Jun 2017 10:28:46 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Stu]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Notes]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=17246</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>Stolen Rhodes bassist Jack Zaferes tells Nick Wells about the highs and lows of playing in a Philadelphia rock band. In this regular feature we shine a light on a select few SBL students regarded by many as ‘ones to...</p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/notes/sbl-student-spotlight-jack-zaferes.html">SBL Student Spotlight &#8211; Jack Zaferes</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com">Online Bass Lessons</a>.</p>
]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/STUDENT_SPOTLIGHT_JACK_ZAFERES.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-17250 size-full" src="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/STUDENT_SPOTLIGHT_JACK_ZAFERES.jpg" alt="" width="1160" height="516" /></a></p>
<p>Stolen Rhodes bassist Jack Zaferes tells Nick Wells about the highs and lows of playing in a Philadelphia rock band.</p>
<p>In this regular feature we shine a light on a select few SBL students regarded by many as ‘ones to watch.’ Throughout the year, we’ll be catching up with a diverse set of breaking and established talent to air their thoughts and experiences about bass playing, tunes and music in general from their own vantage point (the only thing that anyone can do, really). Want to join them? If you're studying with SBL and would like to share your experiences, then please don't hesitate to <strong><a href="https://www.scottsbasslessons.com/contact">Contact Us</a></strong></p>
<h2>Jack Zaferes - Stolen Rhodes</h2>
<p>You’ve got to like Jack Zaferes. For starters, he has that US charisma that we Brits are such suckers for, telling us how much he has gained from studying with SBL (“I can see parts of Scott's teachings in every aspect of my playing!”) – but also because he doesn’t have a shred of arrogance about his career as a bass player. So how did he enter the murky world of bass in the first place, we ask? “Everyone in my family played an instrument,” says Jack. “As soon as I was old enough to jam I was thrown into the bass chair! I think I was in 8th grade when I played my first gig. I was playing in a reggae band and I remember showing up with a huge cabinet and being way too loud! It was a good time.”</p>
<p>Based on mighty riffs from frontman Matt Pillion and guitarist Kevin Cunningham, Jacks’ band Stolen Rhodes remain among the hardest-hitting rock bands around, especially on their new record, Bend With The Wind. Recorded at Dylanava Studios, just outside of Philadelphia, with the assistance of producer David Ivory (Halestorm, The Roots, Silvertide) and mastered by Ted Jensen (The Eagles, John Mayer, AC/DC), the album includes songs that have been extensively road-tested, along with a few that were written right in the studio. “We’ve been on the road constantly for the past year and we’re opening for Blackberry Smoke, Marshall Tucker Band, The Outlaws and Montgomery Gentry for the rest of the tour!”</p>
<p>In addition to his gig with Stolen Rhodes, Jack has also been cutting his teeth with some successful studio tracks with a variety of artists – including Curtis Cooper and Abi Remould. Asked what the secret of good bass playing is, Jack muses: “I try to incorporate a menagerie of styles that are appropriate for whatever tunes I'm playing. Whether it's playing a finger-style walking line over a jazz standard or a wild slap-tap-funk thing, it’s just a matter of using the right paint and the right brushstrokes for what’s needed to make the overall image shine.”</p>
<p>Stolen Rhodes’s album, Bend With The Wind, is out now - <strong><a href="http://www.stolenrhodes.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">www.stolenrhodes.com</a></strong></p>
<h3>What's the music scene like in Philadelphia?</h3>
<p>It’s a vast morphing beautiful ever changing force! Philadelphia has it all from rock to jazz, world, classical, grindcore even funk! My favorite part about living here is the ability to jam with so many different artists of all different genres from around the world!</p>
<h3>What do you remember about your first bass?</h3>
<p>My first bass was an old ‘80s Jackson with the pointy metal band headstock and all. It's still in my collection today. I'll never get rid of that hunk-a-junk!</p>
<h3>What have you gained from being a member of SBL?</h3>
<p>I’ve gained tons from Scott's teachings. I started using his study pieces to build my vocabulary, but I’ve also learned how to truly feel a groove and breathe with a tune. The guy’s got a great way of explaining things to his students that for me is easy to follow.</p>
<h3>Who are your favourite players?</h3>
<p>JACO!</p>
<h3>How do you practice?</h3>
<p>My practice methods vary on a weekly basis. I try to have fun while I practice, so I'll take tunes that I really like and pick them apart. I’ll start by learning the chord changes, then the melody and then I’ll solo over it. I always try to keep things musical. In the beginning I was always practicing scales and modes, but that turned into such a drag! So I'll just pick stuff that's fun now. It could be something by Jamiroquai, Megadeth or even Bach’s Cello Suites. Recently I've been working on the head to Mike Sterns "Mood Swings".</p>
<h3>Tell us about your gear…</h3>
<p>I am a through-and-through Fender Jazz player! I have a 2016 American Jazz Bass and a 2010 Jazz Deluxe. I also play Aguilar amps. Nothing beats that combo of Aguilar and a Jazz Bass! I play Ernie Ball Super Slinkys too.</p>
<h3>What's your best gigging tip?</h3>
<p>Be prepared for everything! Don't just learn the bass part to a tune. Learn the melody, transpose it, solo over it and be ready for any possible outcome!</p>
<h3>What would you be if you weren’t a bass player?</h3>
<p>Probably a Ninja or a Chemist or a mixture of both!</p>
<p><strong>Check out Stolen Rhodes on <a href="https://www.facebook.com/StolenRhodes/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">facebook</a> and Jack in the videos below</strong></p>
<p><iframe width="500" height="281" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/ipkxvlHjkPA?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p><iframe width="500" height="281" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/d5bQLtkv_KA?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p><iframe width="500" height="281" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/4JCpeKnB0YI?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p>To join Jack and our other amazing students within the SBL membership <strong><a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/">click here and grab your 14-day free trial today</a>.</strong></p>
