		<title>SBL Student Spotlight &#8211; Simon Poulton</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/notes/sbl-student-spotlight-simon-poulton.html</link>
		<comments>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/notes/sbl-student-spotlight-simon-poulton.html#respond</comments>
		<pubDate>Thu, 06 Apr 2017 10:08:24 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Stu]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Notes]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=16567</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>In our new weekly feature we’re going to be shining a light on a select few SBL students regarded by many as ‘ones to watch.’ Throughout the year, we’ll be catching up with a diverse set of breaking and established...</p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/notes/sbl-student-spotlight-simon-poulton.html">SBL Student Spotlight &#8211; Simon Poulton</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com">Online Bass Lessons</a>.</p>
]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/STUDENT_SPOTLIGHT_SIMON_POULTON.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-16568 size-full" src="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/STUDENT_SPOTLIGHT_SIMON_POULTON.jpg" alt="" width="1160" height="516" /></a></p>
<p>In our new weekly feature we’re going to be shining a light on a select few SBL students regarded by many as ‘ones to watch.’</p>
<p>Throughout the year, we’ll be catching up with a diverse set of breaking and established talent to air their thoughts and experiences about bass playing, tunes and music in general from their own vantage point (the only thing that anyone can do, really). Want to join them? If you're studying with SBL and would like to share your experiences, then please don't hesitate to <a href="https://www.scottsbasslessons.com/contact">Contact Us</a> as we'd love to share your story and promote your music to the SBL audience!</p>
<h2>Simon Poulton - Bassist. Dad. Darth Maul Approved...</h2>
<p>Simon’s formative days were spent listening to bands like Cake, Barenaked Ladies and Tool, while toying around with his first bass. “I started playing quite late,” he tells us. “I was around 14 years old when some friends suggested that we start a band. The band didn’t make it and I didn’t start to play seriously until I was 16, which is when I met a local bassist called Lincoln Anderson (now sadly passed away) who was a complete inspiration to me. I’ve never looked back.”</p></div>
<p>Being mainly self-taught, Simon is the first to admit that he prefers to concentrate on the framework of a song before adding his own ideas to it. “My practice routine is slightly more sporadic than I’d like, but it will generally consist of plugging into my 3Leaf Enabler Headphone Amp and either transcribing or learning a particular piece. If I’m learning tunes for a gig then I’ll listen to the song as much as I can. I’ll want to be as familiar with it as possible on the gig, which means learning more than just the root notes.”</p></div>
<p>Asked how SBL has informed his bass playing, he tells us: “For me, as excellent as the educational content is, the community is what’s had the biggest impact on my playing. It genuinely functions as a school/academy with all the community benefits that you’d expect of those institutions. It’s not just a lessons website. ”</p></div>
<p>As for gear, Simon is currently using a 1971 Fender Precision, a Lakland 55-01 and a Lakland Darryl Jones Signature. When it comes to amps, he has a Markbass 801, Little Mark 800 and Little Mark II with Barefaced Bass Super Compact and G2 Midget cabinets. Simon also has a huge number of pedals, including: COG Effects Grand Tarkin, Earthquaker Devices Rainbow Machine, Blakemore Effects Deus Ex Machina Fuzz, Line6 M5, TC Electronic Flashback Mini, Boss VB-2 (Japanese Black Label), Digitech Bass Synth Wah, Electro Harmonix Bass Micro-Synth, Dwarfcraft The Great Destroyer, DOD Meatbox SubSynth Reissue and a Fuzzrocious M.O.T.H. “They’ve all been gigged at some point and my pedalboard is always being swapped around for different projects.”<br />
You can check out Simon’s rock/prog project Corybantic at <a href="https://corybantic.bandcamp.com/releases" target="_blank"><strong>corybantic.bandcamp.com</strong></a>. He can also be found backing up London singer/songwriter JoCee at <strong><a href="http://www.joceesmusic.com" target="_blank">www.joceesmusic.com</a></strong></p>
<h3><b>What first encouraged you to pursue a career as a bass player?</b></h3>
<p>I don’t think I’ve ever consciously tried to pursue a career as a professional bassist, but I have been lucky to have toured and recorded with a wide range of bands and artists.</p>
<h3><b>Who are your favourite players at the moment?</b></h3>
<p>It’s not an exhaustive list, but in no particular order; Richard Bona, Michael League, Liam Wilson, Bobby Vega, Justin Chancellor, Jim Creeggan, Gabe Nelson, Sean Hurley, Pino Palladino, Meshell Ndegeocello, James Jamerson, Bob Babbitt, Esperanza Spalding, Steve Lawson and Lincoln Anderson.</p>
<h3><b>Why did you choose SBL? </b></h3>
<p>I had been subscribing to another named bassist's online lessons website, and while that content was of excellent quality and depth, I was drawn to SBL by the addition of the well-populated and supportive forum of users that has grown around it. I moderate over at basschat.co.uk and I know what a difference a supporting group of people like that can be to whatever end.</p>
<h3><b>What's your best gigging tip?</b></h3>
<p>Always listen to what else is happening onstage, but be visually aware too. If you’re performing to a crowd, you’ll also be interacting with other musicians. If you were talking to them you would probably look at them while doing so, but music is also a language, so I try and treat it in the same way. It also serves a practical function when taking onstage directions if you’re subbing on a gig.</p>
<h3><b>Any career highlights?</b></h3>
<p>Every recording I’ve made thus far is a highlight really. I think it’s increasingly difficult to leave a lasting legacy in life, so to have recorded music that you’re proud of floating around in one form or another is a very nice thought.</p>
<h3><b>What would you be if you weren’t a bass player?</b></h3>
<p>I’d almost certainly be a drummer or I’d build effects pedals. If music simply hadn’t come into the picture, I likely would have pursued a (probably disastrous) sports career as a goalkeeper.</p>
<h3><b>What’s been the best thing about 2017 so far?</b></h3>
<p>Probably the release of JoCee’s debut album, which we started working on in May 2016. While she’s essentially a solo artist, the core band have been with her for around 3 years now, so everyone feels very invested in it, which has only added to the creativity. We also started recording a few weeks after the birth of my son, so the whole process has some great memories. It’s on all streaming and digital platforms, but CD &amp; Vinyl are available too.</p>
<h3><b>And the worst?</b></h3>
<p>Brexit &amp; Trump</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">You can check out Simon's blog <strong><a href="http://simonpoulton.tumblr.com/" target="_blank">HERE</a> </strong>and in the videos and tracks below.</p>
